author: Al Jazeera English
description:
In Russia, winters are notoriously severe, with some cities facing extreme cold.
The city of Yakutsk in Eastern Siberia has recorded temperatures as low as -45C.
Such harsh winters are part of daily life for local residents, who are well accustomed to the cold.
People continue their routines despite frozen rivers, snow-covered streets, and biting winds.
Local infrastructure and housing are adapted to withstand the extreme temperatures.
Experts note that Siberian winters remain among the coldest inhabited places on Earth.

Al Jazeera’s Dmitry Medvedenko reports.

description:

Since the war began, her family has been forced to flee multiple times amid drone strikes and shelling.

A fellow Sudanese national helped her reconnect and provided a small tent for shelter.
Her daughter remains in Sudan, now widowed and struggling to care for two young children amid ongoing war.
The mother prays for the end of the violence and hopes to be safely reunited with her daughter.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Civil defence in Gaza is urging international help to bring more bulldozers for body recovery.
Only one bulldozer is available in Gaza City, slowing efforts to recover Palestinians buried under rubble.
Over 9,500 Palestinians remain trapped beneath destroyed buildings, according to civil defence estimates.
Rescue teams work manually with simple tools and old machinery, making the operation slow and hazardous.
A lack of heavy machinery could extend recovery efforts to around three years.
Families see recovery operations as painful but necessary for proper burials and closure.
Civil defence warns many sites across Gaza remain, showing the war’s long-lasting impact.

Al Jazeera’s Ibrahim al-Khalili reports from Gaza City, Palestine.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The High Court of Hong Kong has convicted pro-democracy activist and newspaper founder Jimmy Lai on three charges related to accusations that he undermined China’s national security, as part of a widely scrutinised trial.
Lai now faces the possibility of a life sentence in prison.
On Monday morning, a panel of three judges found Lai, 78, guilty of two counts of conspiring with foreign forces to threaten national security and one count of conspiracy to publish seditious material.
Lai had pleaded not guilty to all the charges. He has been in detention since December 2020, when he was arrested in the midst of a series of antigovernment protests that gripped Hong Kong.
The case has been seen as a test of Hong Kong’s “one country, two systems” principle, which was established after the former British colony was returned to China in 1997.

Al Jazeera’s Patrick Fok reports from Hong Kong.
Tom Grundy is the editor-in-chief of the Hong Kong Free Press.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The border crossing between Burundi and the Democratic Republic of Congo has temporarily reopened.
That's allowed Burundian nationals to return home. 
Burundi closed the frontier after Rwandan backed M23 rebels seized control of the border region last week.

M23 control key cities in the region.
In February they captured Bukavu, the capital of South Kivu.
A month earlier they took over Goma, in North Kivu. 
It says it's focused on restoring peace and security in the area.

Al Jazeera’s Alain Uaykani is in Uvira, where thousands of people are crossing the border into neighbouring Burundi. They include Burundians who were trapped in DRC.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Hong Kong's highest court has found former media mogul Jimmy Lai guilty of sedition and conspiring to collude with foreign powers.
78-year-old Lai is known as the territory's most outspoken critic of Beijing.
He was convicted under a controversial national security law, imposed by Beijing after massive antigovernment protests in 2019.
Lai was arrested five years ago and had pleaded not guilty.
With Monday's conviction he could be in prison for the rest of his life.

Al Jazeera’s Patrick Fok is monitoring developments in Hong Kong. 

Elaine Pearson is the Asia director for Human Rights Watch.
